Difficulties You Faced
1. Variable Shadowing

Initial code:

ArrayList<Employee> employee;

addEmployee(Employee employee)

Problem:

Both variables had the same name.

Lesson:

Use meaningful names.

employees

employee
2. Optional

Initially:

Didn't know when to use it.

Now:

Optional<Employee>

became your preferred return type.

Lesson:

Optional represents the possibility of absence.

3. remove(id)

Initially:

employees.remove(id);

Problem:

Removes by index.

Correct:

employees.remove(employeeObject);

Lesson:

ArrayList has overloaded remove methods.

4. Byte Buffer

Biggest surprise.

byte[] buffer = new byte[1024];

fis.read(buffer);

fos.write(buffer,0,bytesRead);

Lesson:

Java reads chunks of bytes instead of one byte for efficiency.

5. Serialization

Faced:

InvalidClassException

Reason:

serialVersionUID mismatch.

Lesson:

Always define

private static final long serialVersionUID = 1L;
6. Package Access

Faced:

cannot access field

Reason:

Fields were package-private/private.

Solution:

Use getters or make fields public (for learning).

Lesson:

Encapsulation matters.

7. Switch Fall-through

Forgot:

break;

Result:

One menu option executed multiple cases.

Lesson:

Always end each case with break unless fall-through is intentional.

8. Missing Return

loadEmployees()

Forgot:

return new ArrayList<>();

Lesson:

Methods with return types must return on all execution paths.

9. Running Java

Initially:

java Deserialization.java

Caused confusing class-loading issues.

Lesson:

Compile first:

javac

Run:

java ClassName
